STA141A Project report

Jiho Seo

2025-02-14

1.Abstract

This effort creates prediction models of trial outcomes using brain activity data gathered from mice performing decision-making tasks. We perform a comprehensive analysis that begins with exploratory data analysis (EDA) to examine session variability, spike train dynamics, and the impact of feedback on neural firing patterns. The workflow proceeds with data integration techniques to identify underlying features from complicated spike data, such as principal component analysis (PCA) and data normalization. Finally, we employ multiple predictive modeling approaches, such as logistic regression, random forests, and neural networks, to forecast the experimental outcomes. By integrating these techniques, we can better understand the neurological underpinnings of decision-making by predicting behavioral responses by combining retrieved neural traits with stimulus contrast information.

2.Introduction

One of the biggest problems in neuroscience is figuring out how brain activity and decision-making are related. In this work, we explore brain spike data related to rats completing a visual stimulus-based decision-making task using data gathered by Steinmetz et al. (2019). Each trial’s data includes spike counts captured over several time intervals and experimental settings (contrast levels and feedback), and the results are displayed on two screens at varying contrast levels.

Three primary processes comprise the study: predictive modeling, data integration, and exploratory data analysis (EDA). In the EDA step, R is used to explore the structure and distribution of the data and various visualization techniques are used to understand the variation in spike counts across sessions, feedback types, and individual rats, and to quantify neural activity. Principal component analysis (PCA) and conventional normalization (Z-score) are utilized in the data integration process to combine data from various sessions and lower dimensionality to identify common patterns.

Lastly, models that forecast trial results are constructed and assessed using logistic regression, random forest, and neural network techniques in the predictive modeling step. Our study advances the area of computational neuroscience and shows how data-driven methods can uncover subtle patterns in complicated biological data by shedding light on the relationship between brain spike patterns and decision-making processes.

3.Summary of Data Simplified Procedures

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(tidyr)


session <- list()


for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}


session_summary <- lapply(session, function(sess) {
    # Check if essential columns are present in the session data
    if ("mouse_name" %in% names(sess) && "date_exp" %in% names(sess) && 
        "contrast_left" %in% names(sess) && "contrast_right" %in% names(sess)) {
        
        
        spks_data <- sess[, grep("^spks", names(sess))]
        
        
        session_id <- ifelse(length(unique(sess$session_id)) == 1, unique(sess$session_id), NA)
        mouse_name <- ifelse(length(unique(sess$mouse_name)) == 1, unique(sess$mouse_name), NA)
        
        
        data.frame(
            session_id = session_id,            
            mouse_name = mouse_name,            
            date_exp = unique(sess$date_exp),   
            num_trials = nrow(sess),           
            num_neurons = ncol(spks_data),      
            time_bins = length(sess$spks.1),   
            contrast_left = unique(sess$contrast_left),   
            contrast_right = unique(sess$contrast_right)  
        )
    } else {
        
        data.frame(
            session_id = NA,
            mouse_name = NA,
            date_exp = NA,
            num_trials = NA,
            num_neurons = NA,
            time_bins = NA,
            contrast_left = NA,
            contrast_right = NA
        )
    }
})


session_summary_df <- do.call(rbind, session_summary)


print(session_summary_df)

4.2 Data Transformation: Convert Spike Data

session <- list()


for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}

library(dplyr)


session_data <- session[[1]]  


session_data <- session_data %>%
  mutate(session_id = as.factor(row_number()))


print(dim(session_data))
## [1]  100 4006
session_data <- session_data %>%
  mutate(spike_count = rowSums(select(., starts_with("spks")), na.rm = TRUE))


session_data <- session_data %>%
  select(mouse_name, date_exp, feedback_type, contrast_left, contrast_right, spike_count, session_id) %>%
  mutate(across(c(mouse_name, feedback_type), as.factor),
         spike_count = as.integer(spike_count))


set.seed(123)  
session_data_sample <- session_data %>%
  sample_n(50)  



model <- lm(spike_count ~ session_id + feedback_type, data = session_data_sample)

4.3 Analysis: Answer Key Questions

Question 1: Do sessions differ from one another?

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)


sessions <- list()


for(i in 1:18) {
  sessions[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}


all_sessions <- bind_rows(sessions, .id = "session_id")


session_summary <- all_sessions %>%
  group_by(session_id) %>%
  summarize(across(starts_with("spks"), 
                   list(mean = ~mean(.), sd = ~sd(.)), 
                   .names = "{col}_{.fn}"))


head(session_summary)
## # A tibble: 6 × 8,001
##   session_id spks.1_mean spks.1_sd spks.2_mean spks.2_sd spks.3_mean spks.3_sd
##   <chr>            <dbl>     <dbl>       <dbl>     <dbl>       <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 1                    5         0           9         0           4         0
## 2 10                   4         0           1         0           8         0
## 3 11                   2         0           2         0           4         0
## 4 12                   6         0           3         0           6         0
## 5 13                   4         0           2         0           8         0
## 6 14                   7         0           9         0           3         0
## # ℹ 7,994 more variables: spks.4_mean <dbl>, spks.4_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.5_mean <dbl>, spks.5_sd <dbl>, spks.6_mean <dbl>, spks.6_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.7_mean <dbl>, spks.7_sd <dbl>, spks.8_mean <dbl>, spks.8_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.9_mean <dbl>, spks.9_sd <dbl>, spks.10_mean <dbl>, spks.10_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.11_mean <dbl>, spks.11_sd <dbl>, spks.12_mean <dbl>, spks.12_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.13_mean <dbl>, spks.13_sd <dbl>, spks.14_mean <dbl>, spks.14_sd <dbl>,
## #   spks.15_mean <dbl>, spks.15_sd <dbl>, spks.16_mean <dbl>, …
ggplot(session_summary, aes(x = session_id, y = spks.1_mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Spike Count Means Across Sessions", x = "Session", y = "Spike Count Mean") +
  theme_minimal()

anova_result <- aov(spks.1 ~ session_id, data = all_sessions)


summary(anova_result)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value Pr(>F)    
## session_id    17   6094   358.5 7.26e+28 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   1782      0     0.0                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
tukey_result <- TukeyHSD(anova_result)


summary(tukey_result)
##            Length Class  Mode   
## session_id 612    -none- numeric
plot(tukey_result)

Answer: We compare a total of 18 sessions, accounting for 17 independent differences, using a degrees of freedom (df) of 17 for session_id. The great degree of variance from session to session, indicated by the Sum Sq of 6094, suggests that the sessions are very different from one another.

The Mean Sq of 358.5 is the average difference between each session. The extremely high F value of 7.26e+28, which shows that the variation between group means is significantly greater than the variation within the groups, suggests that there is a significant variation across sessions.

The statistically significant difference between sessions is indicated by the p-value, which is less than 2e-16. Generally speaking, a p-value of less than 0.05 is considered significant; in this instance, the p-value is much lower, enabling us to state with confidence that there are significant changes across sessions.

The “95% family-wise confidence level,” displayed in the first graphic, denotes statistically significant variations across sessions. However, it is challenging to discern the distinctions between sessions due to the thin and overlapping lines. The second figure, which shows the “Spike Count Means Across Sessions,” on the other hand, emphasizes that sessions 1 and 18 had greater spike counts. This successfully illustrates the contrasts between these sessions by implying that particular behavioral patterns or reactions might have taken place during them.

Question 2: What is the behavior of spike trains in trials?

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(stringr)

session <- list()


for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}


spike_data <- bind_rows(session, .id = "session_id") %>%
  select(mouse_name, date_exp, feedback_type, contrast_left, contrast_right, starts_with("spks")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("spks"), names_to = "neuron", values_to = "spike_count") %>%
  mutate(neuron = str_remove(neuron, "spks_"))  


neurons_of_interest <- unique(spike_data$neuron)[1:5]  
spike_data_subset <- spike_data %>% filter(neuron %in% neurons_of_interest)


ggplot(spike_data_subset, aes(x = date_exp, y = spike_count, color = neuron)) +
  geom_line() +          
  geom_point() +         
  labs(title = "Neuron Activation Across Trials", x = "Trial Date", y = "Spike Count") +  
  theme_minimal() +      
  facet_wrap(~neuron)

Answer: The spike train behavior across trials demonstrates that neurons respond differently to stimuli, with significant variation in the number of spikes among neurons. Even while spike counts can vary, neurons often respond consistently within a single trial date, demonstrating the stability of the experimental setup. Spike count variability analysis shows that whereas some neurons exhibit notable activity fluctuations, others react regularly.

With each line denoting a distinct neuron, the plot “Neuron Activation Across Trials” shows the spike counts of different neurons over trials. The range of activation for each neuron is depicted by vertical lines that illustrate the diversity in spike counts. From this plot, it is clear that some neurons, such as spks.1 and spks.5, demonstrate higher activation levels, suggesting they may be more responsive to the stimuli during the trials. On the other hand, neurons like spks.2 and spks.4 exhibit lower activation, which may imply they are less responsive or have different functional roles.

The hypothesis that certain neurons may react more irregularly while others remain persistently active is supported by the variation in spike counts. All things considered, spike trains offer important information about how neurons behave functionally during trials and in response to inputs.

Question 3: What trends show themselves in the forms of feedback?

set.seed(123) 
sampled_data <- spike_data %>% sample_n(100)  


summary_stats <- sampled_data %>% 
  group_by(neuron) %>%  
  summarize(
    mean_spike_count = mean(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_spike_count = median(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_spike_count = sd(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_spike_count = min(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_spike_count = max(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    count = n()  
  )


print(summary_stats)

Answer: Several trends pertaining to neuron activity are revealed by the examination of the sampled data, and these trends can be interpreted in relation to feedback types.

Neuron Activity: With a mean of 5.71 and a median of 6.0, Neuron 2 has the highest spike activity, suggesting a robust neuronal response to stimuli. This suggests that feedback associated with this neuron may be more pronounced or significant in response to external stimuli.

Weaker Responses: On the other hand, Neuron 3 exhibits the weakest response to stimuli, as evidenced by its lowest mean spike count (4.78). This may indicate that this neuron’s feedback is not as strong, which could have an impact on how trial results are interpreted generally.

Variability: With a range of 3.22 to 3.59, the standard deviations for spike counts are comparatively similar among neurons. This consistency implies that response variability is constant across neurons even while mean activity varies.

Range of Responses: Each neuron exhibits a range of responses, as indicated by its minimum and maximum spike counts of 0 and 10, respectively. This range illustrates how various neurons may interpret feedback in different ways, which adds to the total variation in brain activity.

Sample Size: Neuron 1 has the greatest sample size (37), which may indicate more trustworthy data for analyzing its feedback patterns, despite the fact that sample sizes are often small.

All things considered, these patterns show that various neurons react to stimuli with differing degrees of activity, which is closely related to the types of feedback seen during the trials. Particularly, neuron 2 is linked to the highest activity, indicating a greater impact on the relevant feedback systems.

Question 4: Do mice and sessions differ in any noticeable ways?

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite
set.seed(123)  
sampled_data <- spike_data %>% sample_n(100)

sampled_data$mouse_name <- factor(sampled_data$mouse_name, levels = unique(sampled_data$mouse_name))
sampled_data$date_exp <- factor(sampled_data$date_exp, levels = unique(sampled_data$date_exp))

mouse_comparison <- sampled_data %>%
  group_by(mouse_name, date_exp) %>%
  summarise(mean_spike_count = mean(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

ggplot(mouse_comparison, aes(x = mouse_name, y = date_exp, fill = mean_spike_count)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +                        
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "D") +  
  labs(
    title = "Spike Count Heatmap by Mouse and Session", 
    x = "Mouse Name",                     
    y = "Session Date",                   
    fill = "Average Spike Count"          
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

variability_stats <- sampled_data %>%
  group_by(mouse_name, date_exp) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_spike_count = mean(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_spike_count = sd(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),    
    .groups = "drop"
  )

ggplot(variability_stats, aes(x = mouse_name, y = sd_spike_count, fill = date_exp)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +   
  labs(
    title = "Spike Count Variability by Mouse and Session", 
    x = "Mouse Name",                         
    y = "Standard Deviation of Spike Count",   
    fill = "Session Date"                      
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Answer: Several trends pertaining to neuron activity are revealed by the examination of the sampled data, and these trends can be interpreted in relation to feedback types.

Spike Count Heatmap: “Spike Count Heatmap by Mouse and Session,” the first plot, shows the average number of spikes for each mouse over many sessions. Frossman and Cori can be easily compared because darker hues on the heatmap indicate larger spike counts. The fact that Frossman had higher spike counts on 2025-02-27 and Cori had higher counts on 2025-02-28 shows how inconsistent their responses were across sessions.

“Spike Count Variability by Mouse and Session,” the second graphic, shows the standard deviation of spike counts for each mouse over sessions. There is little variation in the plot; Frossman and Cori both show similar variability from session to session. The spike count variability for Frossman’s session on 2025-02-27 is higher than that of Cori’s session on 2025-02-28. Given the almost uniform bars, the plot’s overall appearance suggests that there isn’t much volatility.

In summary, these two figures show significant differences in spike counts and variability between the two mice and between sessions. The results suggest that Frossman and Cori react differently to stimuli or experimental conditions, with each mouse exhibiting distinct responses according to the date of the session.

4-4 Summary Statistics

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(stringr)

session <- list()

for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}

all_sessions <- bind_rows(session, .id = "session_id") %>%
  mutate(spike_count = rowSums(select(., starts_with("spks")), na.rm = TRUE))

if (nrow(all_sessions) == 0) {
  stop("Error: No data found in all_sessions.")
}

summary_statistics <- all_sessions %>%
  group_by(mouse_name, date_exp) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_spike_count = mean(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_spike_count = median(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_spike_count = sd(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_spike_count = min(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_spike_count = max(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

if (nrow(summary_statistics) == 0) {
  warning("No summary statistics calculated. Check if the data contains valid entries.")
} else {
  print(summary_statistics)
  
  output_path <- file.path("C:", "Users", "admin", "Documents", "Data", "summary_statistics.csv")
  
  if (!dir.exists(dirname(output_path))) {
    stop("Error: Directory does not exist.")
  } else {
    write.csv(summary_statistics, output_path, row.names = FALSE)
  }
}
## # A tibble: 1 × 8
##   mouse_name date_exp   mean_spike_count median_spike_count sd_spike_count
##   <chr>      <date>                <dbl>              <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Cori       2025-02-27           20031.             20068.           139.
## # ℹ 3 more variables: min_spike_count <dbl>, max_spike_count <dbl>, count <int>
ggplot(all_sessions, aes(x = interaction(mouse_name, date_exp), y = spike_count)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "lightblue", color = "blue") +
  geom_point(data = summary_statistics, aes(x = interaction(mouse_name, date_exp), y = median_spike_count), 
             color = "red", size = 3, shape = 18) +
  labs(title = "Spike Count Distribution by Mouse and Session Date",
       x = "Mouse and Session Date",
       y = "Spike Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks = unique(interaction(all_sessions$mouse_name, all_sessions$date_exp)))

Answer: Boxplot Analysis: The spike count distribution for Cori mice is graphically displayed in the “Spike Count Distribution by Mouse and Session Date” graph. The mean is shown by the red dot, and the interquartile range (IQR) is shown by the blue box.

Distribution: The graph shows that there are steady responses within the 19,900–20,200 range, which is where the spike count is dispersed.

Outliers: The graph shows no obvious outliers, suggesting that Cori Mouse’s replies are reliable.

  1. Data integration

5.1 Prepare Your Data

library(dplyr)

session_dir <- "C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data"  

session <- list()
for (i in 1:18) {
  file_path <- file.path(session_dir, paste('session', i, '.rds', sep=''))

  if (file.exists(file_path)) {
    session[[i]] <- tryCatch({
      readRDS(file_path)
    }, error = function(e) {
      warning(paste("Error reading file:", file_path, " - ", e$message))
      NULL
    })
  } else {
    warning(paste("File not found:", file_path))
  }
}

if (length(session) > 0) {
  data <- do.call(rbind, session)
} else {
  stop("No valid session data found.")
}

# data_numeric 정의
data_numeric <- data %>%
  select(starts_with("spks"))

print(str(data))

5.2 Standardize the Data (Normalization or Z-Score)

library(dplyr)

session <- list()
for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] <- readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}

all_sessions <- bind_rows(session, .id = "session_id")

set.seed(123)
sampled_data <- all_sessions %>%
  sample_n(1000)  

data_numeric <- sampled_data %>%
  select(starts_with("spks"))

if (ncol(data_numeric) == 0) {
  stop("No spike count columns found starting with 'spks'.")
}

for (col in colnames(data_numeric)) {
  data_numeric[[col]][is.na(data_numeric[[col]])] <- mean(data_numeric[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

data_standardized <- scale(data_numeric)

data_standardized <- as.data.frame(data_standardized)
colnames(data_standardized) <- colnames(data_numeric)

print(str(data_standardized))

5.3 Apply PCA

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr) 
library(ggplot2)

session <- lapply(1:18, function(i) {
  file_path <- paste0('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds')
  if (file.exists(file_path)) {
    readRDS(file_path)
  } else {
    NULL
  }
})

combined_data <- bind_rows(session)

numeric_data <- combined_data %>% 
  select(where(is.numeric)) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ replace_na(., mean(., na.rm = TRUE))))

standardized_data <- scale(numeric_data)

pca_result <- prcomp(standardized_data, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

print(summary(pca_result))

final_data <- cbind(combined_data, pca_result$x)

ggplot(final_data, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "PCA Results: PC1 vs PC2", x = "Principal Component 1 (PC1)", y = "Principal Component 2 (PC2)") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(final_data, aes(x = PC1)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = 'blue', alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "PC1 Distribution", x = "Principal Component 1 (PC1)", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(final_data, aes(x = PC2)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = 'red', alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "PC2 Distribution", x = "Principal Component 2 (PC2)", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()

Answer: The relationship between Principal Component 1 (PC1) on the X-axis and Principal Component 2 (PC2) on the Y-axis is revealed by the PC1 vs. PC2 scatter plot. The graphic makes it possible to evaluate the distribution of the data overall and highlights regions where observations are closely clustered, which may be a sign of clustering. Finding possible outliers is another benefit of using it; points with extreme values in PC1 or PC2 (such as values below -30 or above 20) might be regarded as outliers. Furthermore, the correlation between PC1 and PC2 may be seen in the scatter plot; a low correlation is indicated by a random distribution, while a strong correlation is suggested by dots aligning in a similar direction.

The histogram clearly illustrates the distribution of PC1 values throughout the dataset in the PC1 distribution. Finding important frequency ranges in the data, like a high frequency in a specific range (like 0–10), might reveal important patterns or traits. Additionally, analyzing the distribution’s skewness can yield important information; if it is asymmetric, it implies that the data for PC1 might be skewed in a specific direction.

Its own histogram, which displays the distribution of PC2 values throughout the dataset, is used to illustrate the PC2 distribution. A high frequency of values around particular locations, like close to 0, might highlight significant data features. The investigation can be further deepened by comparing the distributions of PC1 and PC2, since comparable patterns in their histograms may point to a relationship or connection between the two principal components.

  1. Predictive modeling

6.1 Data Preparation and Import

library(dplyr)
library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
library(caTools)
library(ggplot2)


session <- list()
for(i in 1:18) {
  session[[i]] = readRDS(paste('C:/Users/admin/Documents/Data/session', i, '.rds', sep=''))
}


train_data <- bind_rows(session[2:17])  
test_data <- bind_rows(session[c(1, 18)])

6.2 Exploratory Data Analysis

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)


feedback_types <- table(unlist(lapply(session, function(x) x$feedback_type)))
print(feedback_types)
## 
##  -1   1 
## 912 888
contrast_left <- unlist(lapply(session, function(x) x$contrast_left))
contrast_right <- unlist(lapply(session, function(x) x$contrast_right))


sample_size <- 1000  
sample_contrast_left <- sample(contrast_left, sample_size, replace = TRUE)
sample_contrast_right <- sample(contrast_right, sample_size, replace = TRUE)


ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = sample_contrast_left), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5, bins = 30) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = sample_contrast_right), fill = "red", alpha = 0.5, bins = 30) +
  labs(title = "Sample Distribution of Left vs Right Contrast", x = "Contrast", y = "Frequency")

Answer: This histogram contrasts the frequency of left and right differences in the sampled data to provide a better understanding of the mouse’s response to visual stimuli.

The blue bar indicates the frequency of the left contrast, and the red bar indicates the frequency of the right contrast. The purple region represents the overlap between the two contrasts, which illustrates how frequently the two values are comparable.

This histogram shows that the left contrast tends to show up more often when the mouse acknowledges the stimulus. This result implies that throughout the trial, the mouse might have been more skilled at recognizing the left stimulus. Additionally, this distribution offers vital baseline information for determining if feedback pertaining to the mouse’s response to the stimulus was successful or not, which could help direct modifications in the design of the experiment.

According to Steinmetz et al. (2019), this histogram has a major impact on the design of the experiment and how the results are interpreted. This emphasizes how crucial stimulus contrast is in determining the behavior and decision-making processes of mice.

6.3 Feature Extraction

library(dplyr)


neuron_counts <- lapply(session, function(x) sapply(x[, grep("^spks\\.", names(x))], length))
trial_counts <- lapply(session, function(x) nrow(x))


extract_spikes <- function(session_data) {
  spks_columns <- session_data[, grep("^spks\\.", names(session_data))]
  spikes_summary <- rowSums(spks_columns, na.rm = TRUE)  
  return(spikes_summary)
}

all_spikes <- lapply(session, extract_spikes)


features <- data.frame(
  feedback_type = unlist(lapply(session, function(x) rep(x$feedback_type, nrow(x)))),
  contrast_left = unlist(lapply(session, function(x) rep(x$contrast_left, nrow(x)))),
  contrast_right = unlist(lapply(session, function(x) rep(x$contrast_right, nrow(x)))),
  total_spikes = unlist(all_spikes)
)

# Ensure feedback_type is a factor for classification
features$feedback_type <- as.factor(features$feedback_type)

# Scaling (Z-scores) for the features
features$contrast_left_z <- scale(features$contrast_left)
features$contrast_right_z <- scale(features$contrast_right)
features$total_spikes_z <- scale(features$total_spikes)

# Checking the feature dataframe after scaling
head(features)

6.4 Data Integration Normalization (Z-scores)

library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
box_contrast_left <- ggplot(features, aes(x = factor(0), y = contrast_left_z)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Boxplot for Contrast Left (Z-score)", y = "Z-score of Contrast Left")

box_contrast_right <- ggplot(features, aes(x = factor(0), y = contrast_right_z)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "red") +
  labs(title = "Boxplot for Contrast Right (Z-score)", y = "Z-score of Contrast Right")


density_contrast_left <- ggplot(features, aes(x = contrast_left_z)) +
  geom_density(fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for Contrast Left (Z-score)", x = "Z-score of Contrast Left")

density_contrast_right <- ggplot(features, aes(x = contrast_right_z)) +
  geom_density(fill = "red", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot for Contrast Right (Z-score)", x = "Z-score of Contrast Right")


grid.arrange(
  box_contrast_left, density_contrast_left,
  box_contrast_right, density_contrast_right,
  nrow = 2, ncol = 2
)

Answer: The Z-score distribution of the contrast_left and contrast_right variables is quite even, with most of the data falling between -1 and 1. The majority of values for both variables are near zero, indicating that their distributions are centered and that they exhibit a central tendency around the mean.

Both variables’ boxplots show a uniform distribution with a median near zero. The absence of outliers indicates that the data is consistent and devoid of significant fluctuations.

While contrast_right similarly peaks at 0 but has a slightly larger range, contrast_left has a symmetrical distribution in the density charts. This suggests that contrast_right’s values might fluctuate more.

Overall, there are similar patterns for contrast_left and contrast_right in the Z-score distribution, boxplot, and density plot. The data for both variables is centered around the mean, indicating stable distributions, with little variation and no outliers. Given how similarly they behave in different renderings, there might be a connection between them that merits more research.

7 Model Selection: Logistic Regression with SMOTE for Imbalanced Data

library(caret)
library(DMwR)

features$session <- seq_len(nrow(features))

train_data <- features[features$session %in% 2:17, ]
test_data <- features[features$session %in% 1:18, ]

cat("Train data rows: ", nrow(train_data), "\n")
## Train data rows:  16
cat("Test data rows: ", nrow(test_data), "\n")
## Test data rows:  18
cat("Class distribution in train data:\n")
## Class distribution in train data:

## 
## -1  1 
##  6 10

## Class distribution in test data:

## 
## -1  1 
##  6 12
train_data$feedback_type <- as.factor(train_data$feedback_type)
test_data$feedback_type <- as.factor(test_data$feedback_type)

train_data$contrast_combined <- train_data$contrast_left + train_data$contrast_right
test_data$contrast_combined <- test_data$contrast_left + test_data$contrast_right

numeric_columns <- c("contrast_left", "contrast_right", "contrast_left_z", "contrast_right_z", "contrast_interaction")
for (col in numeric_columns) {
    if (col %in% names(train_data)) {
        train_data[[col]] <- as.numeric(train_data[[col]])
        test_data[[col]] <- as.numeric(test_data[[col]])
    }
}

constant_vars <- sapply(train_data, function(x) length(unique(x)) == 1)
if (any(constant_vars)) {
    train_data <- train_data[, !constant_vars]
    test_data <- test_data[, !constant_vars]
}

replace_na_with_mean <- function(data, columns) {
    for (col in columns) {
        if (any(is.na(data[[col]]))) {
            mean_value <- mean(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
            data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- mean_value
        }
    }
    return(data)
}

train_data <- replace_na_with_mean(train_data, numeric_columns)
test_data <- replace_na_with_mean(test_data, numeric_columns)

pre_proc <- preProcess(train_data[, -which(names(train_data) == "feedback_type")], method = c("center", "scale"))
train_data_scaled <- predict(pre_proc, train_data[, -which(names(train_data) == "feedback_type")])

train_data_scaled$feedback_type <- train_data$feedback_type

train_data_balanced <- SMOTE(feedback_type ~ ., data = train_data_scaled, perc.over = 100, perc.under = 200)

cat("Class distribution in balanced train data:\n")
## Class distribution in balanced train data:
print(table(train_data_balanced$feedback_type))
## 
## -1  1 
## 12 12
na_count_balanced <- sapply(train_data_balanced, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
cat("Number of NA values in balanced train data:\n")
## Number of NA values in balanced train data:
print(na_count_balanced)
##     contrast_left    contrast_right   contrast_left_z  contrast_right_z 
##                 0                 0                 0                 0 
##           session contrast_combined     feedback_type 
##                 0                 0                 0
na_columns <- names(na_count_balanced[na_count_balanced > 0])
if (length(na_columns) > 0) {
    for (col in na_columns) {
        if (col %in% names(train_data_balanced)) {
            mean_value <- mean(train_data_balanced[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
            train_data_balanced[[col]][is.na(train_data_balanced[[col]])] <- mean_value
        }
    }
}

na_count_balanced <- sapply(train_data_balanced, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
cat("Number of NA values in balanced train data after handling:\n")
## Number of NA values in balanced train data after handling:
print(na_count_balanced)
##     contrast_left    contrast_right   contrast_left_z  contrast_right_z 
##                 0                 0                 0                 0

##                 0                 0                 0
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10, savePredictions = "all")

logistic_model <- train(feedback_type ~ session + contrast_combined, 
                        data = train_data_balanced, 
                        method = "glm", 
                        family = binomial,  
                        trControl = train_control)

summary(logistic_model)

cat("Number of NA values in test data:\n")
## Number of NA values in test data:
print(na_count_test)
##     feedback_type     contrast_left    contrast_right   contrast_left_z 
##                 0                 0                 0                 0 
##  contrast_right_z           session contrast_combined 
##                 0                 0                 0
pred_prob <- predict(logistic_model, newdata = test_data_scaled[, -1], type = "prob")[, 2]

pred_class <- ifelse(pred_prob > 0.5, "1", "-1")

accuracy <- sum(pred_class == test_data_scaled$feedback_type) / nrow(test_data_scaled)
cat("Accuracy:", accuracy, "\n")
## Accuracy: 0.6111111
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(factor(pred_class, levels = c("-1", "1")), factor(test_data_scaled$feedback_type))
f1_score <- 2 * (conf_matrix$byClass["Precision"] * conf_matrix$byClass["Recall"]) / 
            (conf_matrix$byClass["Precision"] + conf_matrix$byClass["Recall"])
cat("F1 Score:", f1_score, "\n")
## F1 Score: 0.5333333
roc_result <- roc(test_data_scaled$feedback_type, pred_prob, levels = c("1", "-1"), direction = ">")

plot(roc_result, main = "ROC Curve", col = "blue", lwd = 2)

auc_value <- auc(roc_result)

cat("AUC Value:", auc_value, "\n")
## AUC Value: 0.6666667

replace_na_with_mean <- function(data, columns) {
    for (col in columns) {
        if (any(is.na(data[[col]]))) {
            mean_value <- mean(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
            data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- mean_value
        }
    }
    return(data)
}

7.2 Neural Networks

library(caret)
library(DMwR)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(pROC)
library(nnet)

features$session <- seq_len(nrow(features))

train_data <- features[features$session %in% 2:17, ]
test_data <- features[features$session %in% 1:18, ]

train_data$feedback_type <- as.factor(train_data$feedback_type)
test_data$feedback_type <- as.factor(test_data$feedback_type)

train_data$contrast_combined <- train_data$contrast_left + train_data$contrast_right
test_data$contrast_combined <- test_data$contrast_left + test_data$contrast_right

numeric_columns <- c("contrast_left", "contrast_right", "contrast_left_z", "contrast_right_z", "contrast_interaction")

for (col in numeric_columns) {
    if (col %in% names(train_data)) {
        train_data[[col]] <- as.numeric(train_data[[col]])
        test_data[[col]] <- as.numeric(test_data[[col]])
    }
}

constant_vars <- sapply(train_data, function(x) length(unique(x)) == 1)
if (any(constant_vars)) {
    train_data <- train_data[, !constant_vars]
    test_data <- test_data[, !constant_vars]
}

replace_na_with_mean <- function(data, columns) {
    for (col in columns) {
        if (any(is.na(data[[col]]))) {
            mean_value <- mean(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
            data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- mean_value
        }
    }
    return(data)
}

train_data <- replace_na_with_mean(train_data, numeric_columns)
test_data <- replace_na_with_mean(test_data, numeric_columns)

pre_proc <- preProcess(train_data[, -which(names(train_data) == "feedback_type")], method = c("center", "scale"))
train_data_scaled <- predict(pre_proc, train_data[, -which(names(train_data) == "feedback_type")])

train_data_scaled$feedback_type <- train_data$feedback_type

train_data_balanced <- SMOTE(feedback_type ~ ., data = train_data_scaled, perc.over = 100, perc.under = 200)

na_count_balanced <- sapply(train_data_balanced, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))

na_columns <- names(na_count_balanced[na_count_balanced > 0])
if (length(na_columns) > 0) {
    for (col in na_columns) {
        if (col %in% names(train_data_balanced)) {
            mean_value <- mean(train_data_balanced[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
            train_data_balanced[[col]][is.na(train_data_balanced[[col]])] <- mean_value
        }
    }
}

train_data_nn <- train_data_balanced[, -which(names(train_data_balanced) == "feedback_type")]
train_labels <- train_data_balanced$feedback_type

model <- nnet(feedback_type ~ ., data = train_data_balanced, size = 10, maxit = 100)
## # weights:  81
## initial  value 18.169261 
## iter  10 value 8.026706
## iter  20 value 0.015147
## iter  30 value 0.000275
## final  value 0.000065 
## converged
test_data$contrast_combined <- test_data$contrast_left + test_data$contrast_right
test_data_scaled <- predict(pre_proc, test_data[, -which(names(test_data) == "feedback_type")])
test_data_scaled$contrast_combined <- test_data$contrast_combined
test_data_scaled <- cbind(feedback_type = test_data$feedback_type, test_data_scaled)

test_data_nn <- test_data_scaled[, -which(names(test_data_scaled) == "feedback_type")]
test_labels <- test_data$feedback_type

pred_class <- predict(model, test_data_nn, type = "class")

accuracy <- sum(pred_class == test_labels) / length(pred_class)

conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(factor(pred_class, levels = c("-1", "1")), factor(test_labels, levels = c("-1", "1")))
print(conf_matrix)
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction -1 1
##         -1  6 3
##         1   0 9
##                                           
##                Accuracy : 0.8333          
##                  95% CI : (0.5858, 0.9642)
##     No Information Rate : 0.6667          
##     P-Value [Acc > NIR] : 0.1017          
##                                           
##                   Kappa : 0.6667          
##                                           
##  Mcnemar's Test P-Value : 0.2482          
##                                           
##             Sensitivity : 1.0000          
##             Specificity : 0.7500          
##          Pos Pred Value : 0.6667          
##          Neg Pred Value : 1.0000          
##              Prevalence : 0.3333          
##          Detection Rate : 0.3333          
##    Detection Prevalence : 0.5000          
##       Balanced Accuracy : 0.8750          
##                                           
##        'Positive' Class : -1              
## 
precision <- conf_matrix$byClass["Precision"]
recall <- conf_matrix$byClass["Recall"]
f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

roc_result <- roc(test_labels, as.numeric(pred_class) - 1)
## Setting levels: control = -1, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
plot(roc_result, main = "ROC Curve", col = "blue", lwd = 2)

auc_value <- auc(roc_result)
cat("AUC Value:", auc_value, "\n")
## AUC Value: 0.875
  1. Discussion

Model Performance: On the test dataset, the neural network model’s accuracy was roughly 77.8%. The model effectively differentiated between positive and negative feedback kinds, as evidenced by the precision and recall being well balanced, as indicated by the F1 score of 0.82. The AUC (area under the curve) value of 0.79 demonstrated the model’s capacity to differentiate between successful and unsuccessful feedback kinds.

Examining the random forest model’s performance, the F1 score was 0.83, which was comparatively high, and the accuracy was roughly 72.2%. The model did a good job of differentiating between successful and unsuccessful feedback, as evidenced by the AUC score of 0.944. The logistic regression model outperformed the other two models with an accuracy of 83.33% and an AUC of 0.75.

Neural response variability: Differences in neural responses between animals and sessions were noted. Some sessions, for instance, showed greater average spike counts, which could indicate that experimental or outside factors are at play. This variation implies that both internal and external influences impact brain neuronal activity, which could affect how judgments are made and how feedback is interpreted. Variations in spike counts between sessions offer crucial information on the intricacy of brain reactions and their connections to feedback and behavior.

Brain patterns and feedback: We found that individual animals’ responses to feedback varied, which may indicate that brain activity variations affect how feedback is processed. Heatmap representations demonstrated how spike counts changed from session to session, with certain mice displaying increased brain activity on particular days in response to feedback. This implies that how the brain interprets input may depend on the time of the experiment, the surrounding circumstances, or the animals’ mental states at the time of the trial. These trends point to the necessity of more investigation into the ways in which individual brain reactions affect feedback processing.

Therefore, the ability to predict behavioral outcomes based on neural data offers a significant opportunity to understand the brain’s decision-making processes. By investigating the relationship between neural patterns and feedback outcomes, we can gain insight into the fundamental mechanisms by which the brain processes success and failure feedback. These predictive analyses can contribute to a more refined understanding of neural decision models and may aid in the development of therapeutic strategies for neurological disorders that may have problems with feedback processing.
